00:38:49.050 --> 00:38:51.450
like to explore that with.

00:38:51.450 --> 00:38:55.780
But I've got a lot to
do in the meantime.

00:38:55.780 --> 00:38:57.830
Yeah. Yeah?

00:38:57.830 --> 00:39:01.900
&gt;&gt; In "Specimens of
Diverse Characters,"

00:39:01.900 --> 00:39:03.860
can you talk a little bit
about your [inaudible]

00:39:03.860 --> 00:39:08.190
and plate making to kind of
achieve some of the [inaudible]?

00:39:08.190 --> 00:39:09.490
&gt;&gt; Russell Maret: Yeah.

00:39:09.490 --> 00:39:10.790
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:39:10.790 --> 00:39:14.090
So in the book "Specimens
of Diverse Characters,"

00:39:14.090 --> 00:39:16.950
except for those two typefaces
and some metal ornaments,

00:39:16.950 --> 00:39:20.750
everything is printed
from photopolymer plates,

00:39:20.750 --> 00:39:22.330
which is primarily what I print

00:39:22.330 --> 00:39:26.360
from because I design my
typefaces and letterforms

00:39:26.360 --> 00:39:31.350
on the computer and I
output a film negative,

00:39:31.350 --> 00:39:35.620
a laser film negative,
and then expose it

00:39:35.620 --> 00:39:39.430
to a photopolymer plate that
makes a raised printing surface.

00:39:39.430 --> 00:39:43.360
And in that book, there
are a number of prints.

00:39:43.360 --> 00:39:49.470
When you think of a
letterpress, you typically think

00:39:49.470 --> 00:39:51.780
of line and void, you know.

00:39:51.780 --> 00:39:56.510
It's either a solid printing
or there's no printing.

00:39:56.510 --> 00:40:00.230
But in this book, there's
a lot of overprinting

00:40:00.230 --> 00:40:06.180
of subtle gradations of
color and tone that were made

00:40:06.180 --> 00:40:11.210
by me just doing pencil
drawings on tracing paper

00:40:11.210 --> 00:40:17.410
and scanning them and outputting
them as halftone film.

00:40:17.410 --> 00:40:22.140
So I think those are the marks
you're talking about, yeah.

00:40:22.140 --> 00:40:25.580
Some of them are quite precise,

00:40:25.580 --> 00:40:31.410
but some of them are really just
me making a field of graphite

00:40:31.410 --> 00:40:35.110
and then scanning it
and using it as texture.

00:40:35.110 --> 00:40:42.400
But it's really wonderful
because, you know,

00:40:42.400 --> 00:40:48.560
when you print one dot
halftone plate, it looks dotty.

00:40:48.560 --> 00:40:51.670
It looks like it's
a bunch of dots.

00:40:51.670 --> 00:40:55.050
When you print a second
different one on top of it,

00:40:55.050 --> 00:40:58.350
it starts to look more
like continuous tone.

00:40:58.350 --> 00:41:04.130
And so, all of the sort of
gradations of color that you see

00:41:04.130 --> 00:41:07.370
in that book are achieved
by printing at least two

00:41:07.370 --> 00:41:12.260
and often four to six plates of
halftones on top of each other.

00:41:12.260 --> 00:41:18.370
And so, there's still a little
bit of dottiness, but, you know,

00:41:18.370 --> 00:41:21.360
from this distance, it's
convincing, you know.

00:41:21.360 --> 00:41:23.290
Yeah. Yeah.

00:41:23.290 --> 00:41:25.840
Anyone else?

00:41:25.840 --> 00:41:27.140
Yes?

00:41:27.140 --> 00:41:32.630
