00:41:38.920 --> 00:41:43.240
3D capabilities, not to print
something in 3D, but actually

00:41:43.240 --> 00:41:47.520
to manipulate forms
in 3D on the screen?

00:41:47.520 --> 00:41:53.780
&gt;&gt; Russell Maret: You know, no,
not because I'm opposed to it.

00:41:53.780 --> 00:41:55.670
I'm one of those
people who works a lot

00:41:55.670 --> 00:41:58.120
on the computer and
doesn't like it.

00:41:58.120 --> 00:42:02.770
So I haven't been
very adventurous

00:42:02.770 --> 00:42:09.140
in learning what the computer
can do beyond drawing outlines,

00:42:09.140 --> 00:42:11.430
which is what I like
to do on the computer.

00:42:11.430 --> 00:42:13.740
The outline gives me the form.

00:42:13.740 --> 00:42:18.750
And I haven't even in
my book character traits

00:42:18.750 --> 00:42:24.290
where I'm experimenting
with digital letterforms.

00:42:24.290 --> 00:42:29.150
Most millennials would
think that what I came

00:42:29.150 --> 00:42:31.890
up with was quite
conservative, I think.

00:42:31.890 --> 00:42:37.000
They still look pretty much
like letterforms, you know.

00:42:37.000 --> 00:42:40.800
And so, I haven't
really gone deeply

00:42:40.800 --> 00:42:43.750
into what something
that's just going to exist

00:42:43.750 --> 00:42:47.360
in digital space can be.

00:42:47.360 --> 00:42:51.920
But I like seeing it.

00:42:51.920 --> 00:42:57.880
It's just that I really,
